“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, cut off from the sea, hopes to restore access to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors besiege the naval headquarters in La Paz dressed in sails.
There are blue flags in public buildings.
The naval bases from Lake Titikaka to the Amazon are marked by the motto: “The sea is our right.
It’s our duty to get him back.”
Across Bolivia, cut off from the sea, the memory of the coast lost in favor of Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century is still alive - as is the desire to roam the waters of the Pacific Ocean again.
After five years of hearings, Bolivia is awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice on 1 October.
“Bolivia is on the rise, has a spirit of unity and balance, and of course believes in a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the international court on big screens across the country in the hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia, so that after decades of adjourned negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate for granting sovereign access to the sea of Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president who will take part in a controversial re-election campaign next year, also has a say in Monday’s decision.
“Our return to the Pacific Ocean is within reach,” he said in late August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia - and even if it did, not much would change.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the authority to allocate Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the international court’s statement comes just six months after hearing the final arguments suggests that the case “wasn’t complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And while there can be no doubt about the Bolivian arguments, it is possible that she has taken a step back in recent years.
“The issue of access to the sea has been taken over by the current Bolivian government,” Zarate said.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric undermined all remaining accommodating Chile, she hinted.
Bolivia and Chile will one day continue to negotiate, but after that it will be very difficult to maintain dialogue.
The two countries have not had embassies since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court’s decision would be unusually quick.
Monday will provide Bolivia with "an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements and achieve mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also rejected the claim that Morales - still one of Latin America's most popular presidents - would use the maritime question as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“Decision is an opportunity to realize that we have to overcome the past.”
