John Edward: No global citizen can do without language skills
Scottish independent schools maintain excellent academic performance and this trend continues in 2018 with another year of extraordinary exam results, further enhancing individual and collective achievement in sports, arts, music and other social activities.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further and higher education, careers as they see fit, and a place in the world as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement tailor-made school curricula, we still perceive modern languages as a popular and demanded subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “When you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you are speaking to his heart.”
It is a strong reminder that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the chart with the highest grade point average among independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved the highest A grade in Mandarin Chinese, 72 percent in German, 69 percent in French, and 63 percent in Spanish.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as basic skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are considered as important as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 per cent of the reasons cited by employers as problems in filling jobs were language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more promising job opportunities are created that require languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses, as long as he has learned a second language, with such a lifelong ability he will have a real advantage in the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 per cent could not speak any foreign language enough to be fluent in conversation, with French being the only language in which the number of people reached double-digit percentages (15 per cent).
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of countries with developed economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will vary according to the languages it teaches.
Some schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK in terms of the future in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, independent schools will always be able to choose from a variety of languages and will be taught by experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the global business environment, languages continue to be fundamentally important for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be called “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this opportunity, diversity and excellent quality.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools.
