North Korea will not unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions had deepened mistrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Institution’s annual general assembly that North Korea has taken “substantial accommodative steps” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing not to expand nuclear weapons and nuclear technologies.
“We don’t see any response from the United States,” he added.
“Without any confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances it is impossible for us to be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s opposition to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual steps, his position was crucial in that he did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised North Korea a security guarantee.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States declared that Pyongyang must first surrender its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to release severe international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. first insists on nuclear disarmament and increases the level of tension through sanctions to achieve its purpose in a coercive way and even by objecting to a ‘declaration to end the war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is an illusion of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our mistrust."
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Trump, which the US president told the United Nations earlier this week.
However, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other side of the nuclear disarmament issue was South Korea instead of the US, disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not get into such a deadlock.”
Nevertheless, Ri’s tone of speech differed dramatically from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil” Trump called Kim a “suicidal mission rocket.”
This year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, sang praise for Kim at the UN for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions had to remain until North Korea was free of nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable, saying it “doesn’t matter if it takes two, three years or five months.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the implementation of the Security Council sanctions must continue rigorously and without exception until we achieve complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to curb funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
In July, he left Pyongyang saying that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemned him for making “gangster demands.”
At a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle both the missile test site and the nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim told him the "corresponding measures" he expected were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to relax enough
The goal of this year’s course at Harvard University is to get all students more sleep in an effort to suppress the growing trend of studying all night long with the help of caffeine.
Researchers have found that students at a world-leading university are often clueless when it comes to the complete basics of taking care of their health.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist in the Brigham and Women’s Clinic, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after a lecture he gave on sleep deprivation and its impact on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was implemented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and sports performance while improving general health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the university decided to open the course when it found that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the work week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one section, the screen shows a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books, and learn about the effects of caffeine, light, and how lack of sleep affects athletic performance, and how important a regular sleep regimen is.
In the next section, participants will learn how a long-term sleep deficit can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons further encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know about it, just as everyone has a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still a culture in which students are proud to have been able to learn all night, he says, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means sleep deprivation has become a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, even against weight gain because sleep deficits put the brain into starvation mode, so they feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his seminars last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a course at the university level.
He hopes that in the next step it will be possible to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before embarking on a challenging study.
Czeisler advises students to set an alarm clock for when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and to become aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emanating from electronic screens and LED lighting that can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
