The National Trust Reveals the Secret Lives of Bats
The new research, which is being conducted on the Scottish Highlands estate, aims to reveal how bats use the land in their food hunts.
We hope that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
A study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the whistling and whistling bats, as well as the bright and water bats in the gardens of Inverewe in the Wester Ross area.
Special recorders are placed on key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
Employees of this organization and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings detects the frequency of calls of bats and the activity of individual species.
They then create a map of their natural environment and a report to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a large scale.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the natural environment are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of environmental management work, such as meadow formation, and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect grasslands and the loss of the environment.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats can also be a danger.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are like eyes when it comes to hunting prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained professionals who regularly conduct surveys, inspections of assemblies, and sometimes rescues.
The organisation even established the first and only dedicated conservation area for bats on the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
“Here in Threave we have a wonderful space for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, a lot of protected trees and all good habitats.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to survive.”
It highlights the importance of inspecting bats before performing maintenance on the property, as it is possible that the unwitting destruction of one maternal assembly site could kill up to 400 females and pups, which would likely destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture, disturb, or destroy their gathering places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to get involved in the aid.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know about many of our species how their populations feed.”
