Current state of red sludge: Concentrations fall in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red slurry concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Florida Commission, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier, there are inconsistent conditions related to the coating, indicating declining concentrations.
Red sludge extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast in the Hillsborough area, but on a smaller number of sites compared to last week.
Red mud was also observed in the Pasco area.
Medium concentrations on or off the coast in the Pinellas area were reported last week, low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough area, high concentrations in the Manatee area, high concentrations on or off the coast in the Sarasota area, medium concentrations in the Charlotte area, high concentrations on or off the coast in the Lee area, and low concentrations in the Collier area.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
